BEGIN_PGML
It is time for the annual Groovy Gathering where everyone from your physics classes dance while a giant disco ball spins overhead. As the party ends, the disco ball is raised back
through a hole in the ceiling. The wheel system shown below controls how fast the disco ball is raised. All the wheels are surrounded in a band of rubber so that no slipping occurs 
between any of them. If wheel A starts from rest and begins turning with an angular acceleration of [`\alpha = [$aA]\, t^2\ \textrm{rad/s}^2`], it takes the disco ball [`[$t]`] seconds
to reach the top. The wheels have radii [`r_A =`] [`[$rA]`] [`m`], [`r_B =`] [`[$rB]`] [`m`], and [`r_C =`] [`[$rC]`] [`m`].


[@ image( "22-R-KM-JL-4.png", width=>[$width], height=>[$height]) @]*

Find the magnitude of the angular velocity of wheel A just before the disco ball reaches the top.

[`\omega_A = `] [_____]{"$wA"}[`\textrm{rad/s}`]

Find the magnitude angular velocity of wheel C just before the disco ball reaches the top.

[`\omega_C = `] [_____]{"$wC"}[`\textrm{rad/s}`]

What will be the angular displacement in radians of wheel C when the disco ball is fully raised?

[`\theta_C = `] [_____]{"$thetaC"}[`\textrm{rad}`]

END_PGML



